text: A planetary structural layer is a type of layer that constitutes at least part of some planet. It is defined as a laminar part of a terrestrial planet or other rocky body large enough to have differentiation by density, with planetary layers having differing physicochemical properties and composition.

The planetary mantle is a type of planetary structural layer, which is at least adjacent to some planetary crust. It is defined as a planetary layer that is an interior part of a terrestrial planet or other rocky body large enough to have differentiation by density. Additionally, the planetary mantle is broadly synonymous with the term "mantle."

A planetary core, also broadly known as a core, represents the innermost structural layer or layers of a planet. This core may be entirely liquid, entirely solid, or comprise both liquid and solid parts, serving as a type of planetary structural layer.

:outer_planetary_core rdfs:subClassOf :planetary_core .
text: outer planetary core is a type of planetary core.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:inner_planetary_core rdfs:subClassOf :planetary_core .
text: inner planetary core is a type of planetary core.
A liquid planetary core is both a type of planetary core and a type of liquid layer. It is defined as a planetary core that is primarily composed of liquid material.
A solid planetary core is both a type of planetary core and a type of solid layer. It is defined as a planetary core that is primarily composed of solid material.

The lithosphere is a type of planetary structural layer, solid layer, and something that at least has part some planetary crust. It is also a type of something that at least has part some entity that is part of the intersection of the planetary mantle and entities that have the quality of being solid. Moreover, the lithosphere is characterized by its quality of being inflexible. It is defined as the outermost shell of a terrestrial-type planet or natural satellite, distinguished by its rigid mechanical properties.

The asthenosphere is a type of planetary structural layer that is characterized by its viscous quality and decreased strength. It is adjacent to the lithosphere. The asthenosphere is defined as a layer of a terrestrial-type planet or natural satellite which is highly viscous, mechanically weak, and ductilely deforming.

Magma is a type of environmental material characterized by having an increased temperature and being primarily located within a planetary structural layer. It is composed mainly of substances that are both environmental materials and have qualities of a liquid. Magma is defined as a mixture of molten or semi-molten rock, volatiles, and solids found beneath the uppermost solid layer of a planetary body. This mixture may also include suspended crystals, dissolved gas, and sometimes gas bubbles.

A trench is a type of depressed landform and is defined as a type of excavation or depression in the ground that is generally deeper than it is wide (as opposed to a wider gully or ditch), and narrow compared to its length (as opposed to a simple hole).

A stream channel is defined as a channel of a watercourse that contains a stream. It is the same as something that intersects with both a channel of a watercourse and something that is at least the location of some stream. This signifies that a stream channel is a type of channel of a watercourse and also a type of something that is at least the location of some stream.

An ocean strait is a type of strait that serves as a location where sea water intersects and connects, specifically acting as a junction between an ocean and a sea. Furthermore, an ocean strait is defined as a strait that connects two oceans.
A river channel is a type of stream channel and is defined as a stream channel which contains a river. It is also a type of entity that corresponds to at least the location of some river.

A slum is a type of dense settlement that constitutes at least part of some city and some urban biome. It is defined as a heavily populated urban informal settlement characterized by substandard housing and where households lack at least one of the following: access to improved water, access to improved sanitation, sufficient living area, durability of housing, or security of tenure.

An undersea trough is a type of trough that is characterized by being at least partially located on the ocean or sea floor, and it is also adjacent to the ocean or sea. Furthermore, it is defined as a trough that is below a marine water body. Additionally, undersea troughs are related to and can be synonymously referred to as deeps, foredeeps, or swales.

An explosive eruption is a type of volcanic eruption defined by a violent process where pressurized magma is forcefully expelled and transforms into volcanic ash. This type of eruption can project a cloud consisting of rocks, dust, gas, and pyroclastic material, which may subsequently collapse, resulting in a pyroclastic flow of hot volcanic matter.

An effusive eruption is a type of volcanic eruption characterized by the flow of lava onto the ground. It is defined as a volcanic eruption during which lava flows onto the ground. This type of eruption involves processes that include, at a minimum, some lava flow process and results in the output of lava.

The igneous intrusion process is a type of rock precursor intrusion process and is characterized by at least having magma as its input and producing an igneous intrusion as its output. Additionally, it is defined as a process whereby rising magma cools and solidifies without reaching the surface. Instead, the cooled and solidified igneous mass crystallizes within the crust to form an igneous intrusion.
A dense settlement is a type of populated place characterized by a high density of buildings and inhabitants.

An igneous intrusion is synonymous with an entity that is both a rock intrusion and significantly composed of igneous rock. It is identified as a category of rock intrusion and is characterized by containing mineral material and being primarily made up of igneous rock. The definition of an igneous intrusion is a mass of rock and minerals that forms when magma cools, solidifies, and undergoes fractional crystallization without reaching the surface.

Tephra is a type of environmental material that is characterized by being at least partially broken and is the output of some explosive eruption. It is defined as fragmental material produced by a volcanic eruption regardless of composition, fragment size, or emplacement mechanism.

Tuff is a type of rock that is an output of some volcanic eruption, specifically made of volcanic ash ejected from a vent during a volcanic eruption. This defines tuff as a rock formed under such conditions.

Scoria is a type of rock and a type of substance that is at least an output of some volcanic eruption. It is defined as a highly vesicular, dark-colored volcanic rock that may or may not contain crystals. Scoria also has an exact synonym: cinder.

Pumice is a type of rock that is also a type of something that is at least an output of some volcanic eruption. It is defined as a volcanic rock that consists of highly vesicular rough textured volcanic glass, which may or may not contain crystals.
A tuff cone is a type of volcanic cone that is primarily composed of tuff and is derived from an ash cone. It is defined as a cone composed of consolidated volcanic ash.
Waste role is a type of role that is defined as a role that is realized in some process wherein the bearer is discarded or not utilized further.

Area of open water is a type of environmental zone that falls under the category of regions that are at least partly comprised of a water body and a planetary surface, and are adjacent to an atmospheric boundary layer. It is defined as an area of a planet's surface which is primarily composed of water in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere, with little to no physical obstruction. Additionally, "area of open water" is also known by the alternative term "open water."

A geological fracture, which is also broadly known as a fracture and relatedly referred to as a fissure, is a type of part found in solid astronomical bodies. It is specifically identified as something situated at the intersection of environmental material and entities that possess the quality of being solid. Moreover, a geological fracture is defined as any separation in a geologic formation, such as a joint or a fault, that divides a mass of rock into two or more pieces.

A geological fault, which is a type of geological fracture, is defined as a planar fracture or discontinuity in a volume of rock, across which there has been significant displacement due to rock mass movement. It is broadly synonymous with the term "fault."

An active geological fault is a type of geological fault and also a type of something that at least participates in some tectonic movement. It is defined as a fault that is likely to become the source of another earthquake sometime in the future, where geologists commonly consider faults to be active if there has been movement observed or evidence of seismic activity during the last 10,000 years. Furthermore, an active geological fault has an exact synonym: active fault.

A vein is both a type of geological fracture and a type of structure that, at least in some locations, contains mineral material. It is defined as a geological fracture that is filled with minerals precipitated out of an aqueous solution.

A dike is a type of rock intrusion and a type of entity that is at least primarily composed of a union of igneous rock and sedimentary rock. It is defined as a sheet of rock that formed in a fracture in a pre-existing rock body. Moreover, dike has an exact synonym, dyke.
A geological joint is a type of geological fracture which is defined as a joint that has no measurable shear displacement. Moreover, it is broadly synonymous with the term "joint."
A shear fracture is a type of geological fracture defined as a geological fracture across which shear displacement has occurred.

Microfracture is identified as a type of geological fracture, which also falls under the category of entities possessing the quality of decreased size. It is defined as a small fracture located in a section of solid material along which additional fracturing is likely to occur. These are viewed as imperfections that exist prior to any fractures formed by the application of stress to a material. Additionally, microfracture is precisely synonymous with the term "Griffith crack."

An atmospheric column is a type of gaseous part of an atmosphere, which possesses the quality of being columnar and is adjacent to both a planetary surface and outer space. It is defined as a vertical pillar characterized by a unit area on a planetary surface and bounded by the top of the atmosphere, utilized for quantifying atmospheric parameters such as pressure, ozone, or precipitable water.

Contaminated air is defined as air which has sufficient concentrations of environmental pollutants such that it may adversely affect a given ecosystem. It is identified as a type of air that intersects with air that has increased levels of a chemical entity, which also plays a role as an environmental contaminant. Essentially, contaminated air is characterized by having elevated levels of substances that not only intersect with chemical entities but also have a significant role as environmental contaminants.

An earthquake is a type of material transport process and is defined as a process during which energy is released in an astronomical body's crust, resulting in the displacement of crustal parts and the generation of seismic waves. It has the exact synonym "quake" and is also relatedly referred to as "temblor" and "tremor."

A tectonic earthquake is a type of earthquake characterized by its association with structural collapse processes, involvement of active geological faults, and its occurrence as a result or within tectonic movements. It is defined as an earthquake caused by the sudden release of energy accumulated in an astronomical body's crust, where the elastic strain placed on constituent rock masses leads to their fracturing.

A megathrust earthquake is a type of tectonic earthquake that occurs at subduction zones at destructive plate boundaries, specifically convergent boundaries. This kind of earthquake involves at least some convergent plate boundary as a participant. These interplate earthquakes are considered the planet's most powerful, with moment magnitudes that can exceed 9.0, according to its definition.

A polluted lake is defined as a lake with concentrations of environmental contaminants high enough to harm the ecosystems associated with it. It is identified as a type of lake and also falls under the category of entities that are at least composed primarily of contaminated water. Furthermore, a polluted lake is equivalent to an entity that is an intersection of a lake and an entity composed primarily of contaminated water.

Sodium chloride salt is a type of salt material and a type of something that is at least composed primarily of some sodium chloride. It is defined as a mineral material composed primarily of sodium chloride. Additionally, sodium chloride salt has a broad synonym, which is simply "salt."

Glacial abrasion is a type of glacial erosion process that involves at least some rock as a participant. It is defined as an erosional process during which debris in the basal ice scrapes along the bed, polishing and gouging the underlying rocks, similar to how sandpaper works on wood. Glacial abrasion is broadly synonymous with both abrasion and scouring, and it is exactly synonymous with glacial scouring.

Glacial plucking is a type of glacial erosion process and also a type of process that involves rocks as at least one of its participants. It is defined as an erosional process during which pieces of bedrock are cracked off due to the mechanical force of a moving glacier. Additionally, glacial plucking is broadly synonymous with quarrying and exactly synonymous with glacial quarrying.

Glacial ice thrusting is a type of glacial erosion process that involves at least some sediment as a participant. It is defined as an erosional process during which a moving glacier, which has frozen to its bed, surges forward and moves large sheets of sediment frozen to the glacial mass. Glacial ice thrusting is also exactly synonymous with ice thrusting.
Water mass is a type of body of liquid and something that is at least composed primarily of some liquid water. It is defined as a mass of water.
A marine water mass is a type of water mass and is something that is at least composed primarily of sea water. It is defined as a mass of marine water.

The coast is defined as the area where land meets the sea, ocean, or lake, which is an intersection of a compound astronomical body part and a planetary landmass that at least overlaps with a union of the ocean, sea, and lake. Additionally, the coast is categorized as a type of compound astronomical body part, a type of area that at least overlaps with some planetary landmass, and a type of area that at least overlaps with the union of the ocean, sea, and lake.

A lake coast is a type of coast that at least partially overlaps with some part of a lake. It is defined as the general region of indefinite width that extends from a lake inland to the first major change in terrain features.

A tsunami is a type of mass liquid flow and is also known as a seismic sea wave or tidal wave. It is defined as a process during which a series of waves is generated in a water body, typically an ocean or large lake, by the displacement of a large volume of water. Such phenomena can be triggered by various disturbances including earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, other underwater explosions (like detonations of underwater nuclear devices), landslides, glacier calvings, meteorite impacts, and more, above or below water. Additionally, a tsunami is characterized by involving at least something that is a union of entities such as oceans, seas, and lakes.

Mass wasting is a type of material transport process, which is also broadly synonymous with mass movement and exactly synonymous with slope movement. This process involves, at the very least, some material accumulation and decumulation processes. Mass wasting is characterized by the participation of slopes and involves materials that are an intersection of environmental materials and those that possess the quality of being solid. The definition of mass wasting highlights it as the geomorphic process where solid environmental materials such as soil, sand, regolith, and/or rock move downslope, typically as a mass. This movement is largely driven by gravity but is often influenced by water and its content, as seen in submarine environments and mudslides.

An avalanche is a type of mass wasting flow and can be defined as a mass wasting flow during which snow rapidly flows down a sloping surface. It is a phenomenon that involves participants which are at the intersection of environmental materials and entities that are composed primarily of snow. Furthermore, an avalanche is also known by its exact synonyms, snowslide and snowslip.

The landslide process is a type of mass wasting, which involves a large mass of earth and rocks moving down a hill or a mountainside. This process can include various participants such as scree, rock, soil, sediment, mud, and sand. Additionally, the landslide process is also known as a landslip.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:rockfall rdfs:subClassOf :mass_wasting .
text: rockfall is a type of mass wasting.

Geological subsidence is a type of material transport process that involves the downward shifting of a geological surface relative to a datum, such as sea level. This process can be a part of or involve participants that include submerged beds and planetary landmasses. Moreover, geological subsidence is broadly synonymous with subsidence.

A mudslide is a type of mass wasting and is a type of phenomenon that involves at least one participant which is an intersection of an environmental material and an entity that is composed primarily of mud.

Mass wasting flow is a type of mass wasting with a definition that states it as a form of mass wasting during which the moving materials behave similarly to a flowing fluid, often involving water, air, and ice to enable fluidlike motion of the material. Additionally, mass wasting flow is broadly synonymous with "flow."

A mudflow is a type of mass wasting flow that occurs when environmental material that includes an intersection of substances with increased levels of liquid water combines with materials that are a union of clay and mud. This type of flow is defined as a form of mass wasting which involves a very rapid to extremely rapid surging flow of debris that has become partially or fully liquified by the addition of significant amounts of water to clay-rich source material. Additionally, "mudflow" has an exact synonym, which is "mud flow."

Debris flow is a type of mass wasting flow and is defined as a mass wasting flow during which water-laden masses of soil and fragmented rock rush down the slopes of elevations, funnel into stream channels, entrain objects in their paths, and form thick, muddy deposits on valley floors. It involves various participants including valleys, rocks, soil, and stream channels.

Lahar is a type of mudflow that involves environmental material with increased levels of volcanic rock, tephra, tuff, and volcanic soil. It also involves at least one participant from either a volcano or a volcanic cone. Lahars are defined as mudflows or debris flows composed of a slurry of pyroclastic material, rocky debris, and water, flowing down from a volcano, typically along a river valley.

Sturzstrom is a type of landslide process, defined as a landslide that possesses a significant amount of kinetic energy, enabling it to move horizontally much further than its initial vertical drop – potentially as much as 20 or 30 times the vertical distance. This is in contrast to a normal landslide, which usually travels a horizontal distance less than twice the distance of the material's vertical fall.

Volcanic ash is defined as an environmental material consisting of fragments of pulverized rock, minerals, and volcanic glass. It is created during volcanic eruptions, including explosive volcanic eruptions, phreatomagmatic eruptions, and during transport in pyroclastic density currents, with particles measuring less than 2 millimeters in diameter. Volcanic ash is the same as the intersection of ash and at least one output of some volcanic eruption. It is also a type of ash and is characterized as an output of volcanic eruptions. Additionally, volcanic ash is primarily composed of silicon dioxide.

The ash fall process is a type of precipitation process that occurs as part of a volcanic eruption. It involves the gravitational pull of volcanic ash, which is formed during an explosive volcanic eruption, phreatomagmatic eruption, or during material transport in pyroclastic density currents, towards the planetary surface. This process not only involves the planetary surface but also includes tephra, volcanic ash, and entities that are a combination of water bodies and the atmosphere as participants.

The hydrological precipitation process is a type of precipitation process and is also broadly synonymous with precipitation. It is defined as a process during which any product of the condensation of atmospheric water vapor is pulled to the planetary surface by gravity. Furthermore, the hydrological precipitation process is a type of process that requires input from an entity that is an intersection of environmental material and an entity that is composed primarily of water, and it also outputs from the hydrological condensation process.

Hydrological evaporation is a type of hydrological process and a type of evaporation, specifically referring to something that necessitates the input of some liquid water. It is defined as the evaporation of water, generally as part of a planetary water cycle.

Soil degradation, which is a type of land degradation, is defined as a process resulting in a change in soil health status. This change leads to a diminished capacity of the ecosystem in which the soil occurs to provide goods and services for its beneficiaries.

Soil erosion is a type of planetary erosion and is a process in which exogenic processes remove soil from one location on the Earth's crust and transport it to another location where it is deposited. This type of erosion is something that involves soil as at least one of its participants.

Coastal flooding is a type of flooding that involves several participants including at least some coast, as well as entities that are a union of oceans, seas, and lakes, and also a union of lakes and marine water bodies. Furthermore, coastal flooding is defined as a process in which normally dry, low-lying land near a coast is flooded by sea water.

Riverine flooding is a type of flooding characterized by a process where the flow rate of river water exceeds the capacity of its channel, leading to the flooding of the neighbouring land. Especially, bends and meanders in a river channel are highly susceptible to such flooding.

Flash flooding is a type of flooding and is also a type of event that involves at least some depressed landform as a participant. It is defined as a process in which low-lying land is inundated with water for a short period of time, usually resulting from precipitation or a breach in the container of a water body.

A flood is categorized as a type of water body and is defined as an unusual accumulation of water above the ground caused by factors such as high tide, heavy rain, melting snow, or rapid runoff from paved areas. It is also recognized as a phenomenon that forms as a result of some flooding.

A coastal flood is a type of flood that occurs when large amounts of water from marine water bodies or large lakes are displaced onto usually dry land, often due to processes such as high winds or seismic activity. This type of flood is characterized by its occurrence along coasts and is formed as a result of coastal flooding. The definition of a coastal flood highlights its nature and the conditions under which it forms.
A riverine flood is a type of flood that is continuous with and formed as a result of riverine flooding. It occurs when a river's flow rate exceeds the capacity of its channel.

A flash flood is a type of flood that is specifically formed as a result of flash flooding. It is defined as a rapid flooding of geomorphic low-lying areas, which can be triggered by heavy rain associated with severe thunderstorms, hurricanes, tropical storms, or meltwater from ice or snow flowing over ice sheets or snowfields. Additionally, flash floods may occur following the collapse of either a natural ice or debris dam, or a human-made structure such as a dam. What sets flash floods apart from regular floods is their timescale, which is less than six hours.

Storm surge is a type of coastal flood and is considered a phenomenon that forms as a result of specific storm surge processes. It is defined as a coastal flood caused by low-pressure weather systems, including tropical and strong extratropical cyclones. The severity of a storm surge is influenced by factors such as the shallowness and orientation of the water body relative to the storm path, as well as the timing of the tides.
A meteotsunami, which is a type of tsunami, is defined as a tsunami that is caused by atmospheric processes and differences in air pressure. It also has an exact synonym, rissaga.

Storm surge process, a type of coastal flooding, is defined as a coastal flooding process that is triggered by low-pressure weather systems, including tropical cyclones and strong extratropical cyclones. The severity of the storm surge process is influenced by factors such as the shallowness and orientation of the water body relative to the storm path, and the timing of tides.

Areal flooding is a type of flooding that occurs when flat or low-lying areas, characterized as being either plain or depressed landforms, become inundated with water. This happens because the input of water exceeds the capacity for infiltration, evaporation, or runoff.

Urban flooding is a type of flooding that occurs in areas that are either cities or dense settlement biomes. It is defined as a flooding process where land or property in a built environment, especially in more densely populated areas, becomes inundated. This happens because the rate of water input exceeds the drainage capacity of the environment's drainage systems.

Snowmelt is a hydrological melting process where water is produced by the melting of snow and becomes part of the hydrological surface runoff. This process requires snow as an input and results in the output of fresh water.

The hydrological melting process is identified as a specific type of melting and is categorized under hydrological processes. This process is also recognized as part of or related to some thawing processes. It is characterized by involving inputs that are at the intersection of liquid water and substances with the quality of being solid. Similarly, the outputs of the hydrological melting process include substances at the intersection of liquid water and entities with the quality of being liquid. The definition of the hydrological melting process is a melting process during which water-based ice, snow, or other solid phase water transitions into a liquid phase.

Icemelt is a type of hydrological melting process, which is defined as a process in which water is produced by the melting of ice and becomes part of the hydrological surface runoff. This process at least requires water ice as an input and produces fresh water as an output. Additionally, icemelt has an exact synonym: ice melt.

Meltwater is a type of liquid water and also a type of substance that is at least formed as a result of some hydrological melting process. It is defined as the water released by the melting of snow or ice, including glacial ice, tabular icebergs, and ice shelves over oceans.

Melting is a type of material transformation process that involves a specific interaction with environmental materials. It includes an input process where at least one solid environmental material is involved, and an output process where the resulting substance is an environmental material with the quality of a liquid. Furthermore, melting is defined as a material transformation process which results in the phase transition of a substance from a solid to a liquid. In addition to "melting process" being an exact synonym for melting, "fusion" is also considered a related synonym.

The condensation process is a type of material congelation process and it is also a type of process that requires an input intersecting environmental material with a quality of being a gas. Moreover, condensation is defined as a process during which a gas undergoes a phase transition into a liquid.

The chemical precipitation process is a specific type of precipitation process, defined as a process in which a portion of some solid substance segregates from a material in which that substance or its precursors were dissolved. This segregation and settling occur due to forces such as gravity or centrifugal force. The segregation may happen because the solubility limits of the precipitating substance are exceeded or due to a chemical reaction that forms a solid product from aqueous reagents.

The desublimation process is a type of material congelation process and has the broad synonym "deposition". It is defined as a process in which a portion of some gas undergoes a phase transition into a portion of some solid. This process involves an input that is at least an intersection of something environmental and something that has the quality of a gas. Similarly, its output is at least an intersection of something environmental and something that has the quality of a solid.

The sublimation process is a type of material transformation process that involves a specific input and output. The input required for the sublimation process is a material that intersects with environmental materials and possesses the quality of being solid. Conversely, the output from the sublimation process is a material that intersects with environmental materials and possesses the quality of being a gas. Furthermore, sublimation is defined as a process during which a portion of some solid undergoes a phase transition into a portion of some gas.

The tectonic uplift process is a type of tectonic movement and also falls under the category of phenomena involving at least one participant that is either a submerged bed or a planetary landmass. It is defined as a geomorphologic process where a geological surface moves upward relative to a datum, such as sea level, due to forces excluding isostatic responses to unloading.

Atmospheric subsidence is a type of material transport process, which includes katabatic wind as at least a part of it, and involves a participant that is the intersection of air and at least part of an atmosphere. It is defined as a material transport process during which a mass of air moves through an atmosphere towards a planetary surface.

The lava flow process is a type of mass liquid flow and is characterized by at least having some lava and some planetary landmass as participants. It is defined as a process in which a volume of lava emitted during an effusive eruption moves along a solid surface.

Igneous extrusion is a type of volcanic feature and something that is at least composed primarily of igneous rock. It is defined as a mass of igneous rock formed when hot magma flows out (extrudes) onto a planetary surface as lava or explodes violently into the atmosphere to fall back as pyroclastics or tuff.

A clastic dike is a type of sedimentary intrusion and also a type of dike, which is defined as a dike formed when sediment fills a pre-existing fracture in a mass of rock. It is exactly synonymous with clastic dyke.

Stock is a type of igneous intrusion and also falls into the category of entities formed as a result of the intersection between igneous intrusion processes and planetary erosion. Furthermore, a stock is defined as a discordant igneous intrusion with a surface exposure of less than 100 square kilometres, distinguishing it from batholiths solely based on its smaller size.

A laccolith is a type of rock intrusion characterized by being a sheet intrusion, or concordant pluton, that has been injected between two layers of sedimentary rock. The defining aspect of a laccolith is that the pressure of the magma is sufficiently high to force the overlying strata upward. This action gives the laccolith a distinctive dome or mushroom-like shape, while maintaining a generally planar base.
A lopolith is a type of rock intrusion, characterized by being a large igneous intrusion that is lenticular in shape with a depressed central region.

A phacolith is a type of rock intrusion, defined as an intrusion that is parallel to the bedding plane or foliation of folded country rock. More specifically, it is usually lens-shaped and occupies either the crest of an anticline or the trough of a syncline.

Sill is a type of rock intrusion and it is defined as a tabular sheet intrusion that has intruded between older layers of sedimentary rock, beds of volcanic lava or tuff, or along the direction of foliation in metamorphic rock. Furthermore, sill is exactly synonymous with concordant intrusive sheet.

The rock precursor intrusion process is a type of material transport process that involves the participation of rock. Additionally, this process includes the involvement of elements that are either sediment, lava, or magma. It is defined as a process whereby the precursors of rock, such as magma or sedimentary particles, fill a fracture in a mass of rock.

A habitat is a type of ecosystem and is part of at least some biosphere. It is determined by the population of organisms within it. Moreover, a habitat is defined as an environmental system that can sustain and allow the growth of an ecological population.

The area of perennial water ice is defined as a type of environmental zone that is part of, or adjacent to, some planetary surface, including areas of perennial ice or snow, and the atmospheric boundary layer. Specifically, it is an area of a planet's surface primarily composed of water ice, present throughout multiple years, and in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere with little to no physical obstruction.

The recycling process is identified as a type of environmental system process. It is defined as a process during which materials considered waste are separated and converted into a form that can be utilized as input by the same processes that generated them. This process is also exactly known by several synonyms including "Recycling-Prozess," "proceso de reciclaje," "processo di riciclo," and "資源回收."

The carbon bearing gas emission process is a specific kind of hydrocarbon gas emission process, characterized by being an intersection of entities that, at the very least, possess some qualities of a gas and output something that contains carbon atoms as a part of its composition. It is defined as any environmental process that results in the output of a carbon-bearing gas. Additionally, the carbon bearing gas emission process is broadly synonymous with the term carbon emission process.

The land consumption process is identified as a form of anthropisation. It is characterized as a process where natural ecosystems spread across a land area are eliminated and substituted by ecosystems created by humans. Additionally, this process falls under a category that inherently involves the transformation and degradation of land. It also entails the participation of planetary landmasses.

A human dwelling is a type of domestic building with a specific definition: a self-contained constructed feature used by one or more households as a home. This can include houses, apartments, mobile homes, houseboats, or other 'substantial' structures. Typically, a dwelling encompasses nearby outbuildings, sheds, etc., within the property's curtilage, excluding any 'open fields beyond'. The concept of a dwelling holds significance in various contexts, including search and seizure, conveyancing of real property, burglary, trespass, and land use planning.

The area of perennial snow is categorized under environmental zones, specifically defined as an area of a planet's surface which is primarily composed of snow, present throughout multiple years. This zone is in contact with an atmospheric column that extends from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere with little to no physical obstruction. It is part of, or adjacent to, the atmospheric boundary layer and constitutes a segment of the planetary surface that is, or is part of, an area of perennial ice or snow.

An area of perennial ice or snow is classified as a type of environmental zone and is also referred to by the alternative term "perennial ice/snow." This zone is defined as an area of a planet's surface primarily composed of snow or water ice that persists throughout multiple years. It is in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere, with little to no physical obstruction. Additionally, an area of perennial ice or snow is described as intersecting with regions that are either solely composed of snow or are at the intersection of the planetary surface and areas primarily composed of ice. Furthermore, it is adjacent to some atmospheric boundary layer.

Regolith is a type of solid layer characterized by several qualities and components. It is defined as a layer of loose, heterogeneous, superficial material that covers solid rock, including dust, soil, broken rock, and other related materials. This layer is composed of at least some dust and is also made up of a union of pieces of rock and soil. Additionally, regolith possesses the quality of being at least partially broken. Furthermore, it is adjacent to some planetary crust, emphasizing its close relationship with the underlying solid rock formation.

Continental crust is a type of planetary structural layer, which is part of the planetary crust. It is defined as a layer of igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic rocks that forms continents and the areas of shallow seabed close to their shores, known as continental shelves.
Oceanic crust is a type of planetary structural layer and is part of some planetary crust. It is defined as the uppermost layer of the oceanic portion of a tectonic plate.

The Mohorovicic discontinuity, often simply called the Moho, is a specific type of planetary structural layer. It is defined as the boundary between the Earth's crust and the mantle, signifying a change in composition. This discontinuity is also exactly synonymous with both "Moho" and "Mohorovičić discontinuity."
Bedrock is a type of rock with a definition as a lithified mass of rock that lies under the loose softer material (regolith) at the surface of the Earth or other terrestrial planet.

The area of barren land is categorized as a type of terrestrial environmental zone, which also qualifies as a type of region that is at least adjacent to some atmospheric boundary layer. It is defined as an area of a planet's surface primarily composed of bedrock, desert pavement, scarp rock, talus, material exposed by slides, volcanic material, glacial debris, sand, material exposed during strip mining, gravel, and other accumulations of earthen material in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere, with little to no physical obstruction. Additionally, the area of barren land is alternatively referred to as Barren Land (Rock/Sand/Clay).

A fumarole-derived ice tower is a type of elevated landform, surface landform, and cryoform, which is at least adjacent to some ice cave and composed primarily of water ice. It is defined as a hollow tower of ice formed by the freezing of steam escaping a fumarole. Additionally, "ice chimney" and "ice tower" are related synonyms for a fumarole-derived ice tower.

Aeroform is defined as a part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of a continuous volume of gaseous or aerosolized material held in shape by one or more environmental processes. It is identical to an entity that is the intersection of a gaseous astronomical body part and entities that are at least located in some atmosphere and at least composed primarily of air and aerosol. Moreover, aeroform is a type of gaseous astronomical body part, a type of entity that is at least located in some atmosphere, and a type of entity that is at least composed primarily of a union of air and aerosol.

Cloud is a type of meteor and also a type of entity that is at least composed primarily of aerosolized liquids, aerosolized solids, and entities that are a combination of crystals and entities that at least possess the quality of being frozen. Furthermore, a cloud is defined as a visible mass of aerosolized liquid droplets or frozen crystals suspended in an atmosphere above the surface of a planetary body. Additionally, "cloud mass" is an exact synonym for cloud.

Polar stratospheric cloud is a type of water-based cloud and it has an exact synonym, nacreous cloud, as well as a related synonym, PSC. It is defined as clouds that form in the winter polar stratosphere at altitudes of 15,000–25,000 meters, supporting chemical reactions that produce active chlorine and remove gaseous nitric acid, catalyzing ozone destruction.
A sparsely populated settlement is a type of populated place that is defined as a settlement with a low density of buildings and inhabitants.

Rural settlement is a type of sparsely populated settlement, an anthropised terrestrial environmental zone, and something that constitutes at least part of some rural area. It is defined as a settlement which has a lower population density than a town, city, or other urban environment and is primarily used for agricultural or pastoral activity.

A formal settlement is a type of populated place that is defined as a settlement which has been established and is managed through officially sanctioned processes and is recognized as legal by a competent authority.

An informal settlement is a type of populated place characterized by a settlement that is not associated with or directed by official planning processes and typically lacks municipal services and infrastructure, such as sanitation, water services, and waste management services.
A legal settlement is a type of populated place that is defined as a settlement on land that the inhabitants have a legal claim to.
An illegal settlement is a type of populated place, defined as a settlement on land that the inhabitants have no legal claim to or occupy illegally.
A primary forest is a type of forest ecosystem, defined as a forest that originally covered a region before changes in the environment brought about by people. (Source: PHC).

The carbon dioxide emission process is a type of carbon-bearing gas emission process and is defined as any environmental process that releases carbon dioxide gas into the atmosphere. It is also a type of process that outputs something which intersects with carbon dioxide and possesses qualities of a gas. Furthermore, the carbon dioxide emission process is classified as a type that is at least causally upstream of or within some greenhouse effect.

Carbon dioxide emission is a type of atmospheric carbon dioxide and is also defined as a type of output from a carbon dioxide emission process. Additionally, carbon dioxide emission is defined as a volume of carbon dioxide gas emitted by a carbon dioxide emission process.

An all-season road is a type of road characterized by being usable across all seasons, which is its definition. It is also precisely known as an all-season road and is relatedly referred to as a permanent road.

A rural area is a type of anthropised terrestrial environmental zone and also a type of area that at least overlaps some vegetated area. It is defined as an area which is outside of a town, city, or urban area, primarily used for agriculture or pastoralism, and may contain rural settlements.

A village is characterized as a type of populated place and also as a type of entity that constitutes at least a part of some village biome. It is defined as a clustered human settlement or community, which is larger than a hamlet but smaller than a town. The population of a village can vary from a few hundred to a few thousand. While villages are often found in rural areas, the term "urban village" is applied to certain urban neighborhoods as well. Typically, villages are permanent settlements with fixed dwellings, although transient villages can exist. The dwellings within a village are usually situated close to one another, unlike in a dispersed settlement where they are spread widely across the landscape.
An oligotrophic lake is a type of lake that is primarily composed of oligotrophic water, which is nutrient-poor. This defines an oligotrophic lake as a lake that has nutrient-poor water.
A mesotrophic lake is a type of lake that is primarily composed of mesotrophic water, characterized by medium nutrient levels which allow for moderate productivity.

A piece of plastic is defined as a mass of solid material that is primarily composed of synthetic plastic. This definition places it as a type within both the categories of solid material masses and items composed primarily of synthetic plastic. Additionally, "piece of plastic" is exactly synonymous with "Plastikstück," "pedazo de plástico," and "pezzo di plastica."
A nurdle is a type of plastic pellet, defined as a plastic pellet produced in a size that allows it to be rapidly melted and used as input for further downstream manufacturing processes.

A Key Biodiversity Area is a type of area of protected biodiversity and also a type of entity that at least overlaps some ecosystem. It is defined as an environmental zone which contains, as determined by an officially mandated selection process, one or more ecosystems which include, as parts, ecological communities of global significance for conservation due to their vulnerability and irreplaceability. An alternative term for Key Biodiversity Area is an important site. Moreover, Key Biodiversity Area has narrow synonyms including Alliance for Zero Extinction Sites, Ecologically and Biologically Significant Area, IUCN Important Site for Freshwater Biodiversity, Important Bird Area, Important Mammal Area, Important Plant Area, Important Site for Freshwater Biodiversity, Prime Butterfly Area, and Ramsar Sites.

Public infrastructure is equated to entities that intersect the categories of human construction and those that participate, at least minimally, in the utilization of an environment for infrastructure and utilities. It is identified as a subset of human construction and also as a category encompassing entities that engage in some form of environmental usage for infrastructure and utilities purposes. Public infrastructure is defined as the system of public works within a country, state, or region, which comprises roads, utility lines, and public buildings. Additionally, "infrastructure" is considered a broad synonym for public infrastructure.
A public road is a type of road and is considered a part of public infrastructure, or at least a portion of it. It is defined as a road that is publicly accessible.
A public building is a type of building that is part of, or at least partially part of, some public infrastructure. It is defined as a building which is publicly accessible.

Utility lines are a type of manufactured product that forms at least part of public infrastructure and participate in the usage of an environment for infrastructure and utilities. Moreover, a utility line is defined as a cable used to transmit electricity from its point of production to its point of consumption.
A public utility line is a type of utility line that is defined as a utility line which services the public power grid.

An illegal informal settlement is a type of informal settlement, defined as a populated place where groups of housing units have been constructed on land that the occupants have no legal claim to, or occupy illegally, or where dwellings are not in compliance with current planning and building regulations. Additionally, "informal settlement" is a broad synonym for illegal informal settlement.

The material extraction process is identified as a type of environmental system process and is also categorized under planned processes. Furthermore, it is characterized as a type of process that necessarily involves, at least in part, some material transport process and includes the participation of some environmental material. The definition of the material extraction process is described as a planned process during which a portion of environmental material is removed from a material entity.
Fire is a type of combustion process. It is defined as a process whereby rapid and exothermic oxidation of a material through a combustion process releases heat, light, and other products.

Wildfire is a type of conflagration and has an exact synonym, wildland fire. It is known to occur in some terrestrial biome and involves areas that are either rural or vegetated. Additionally, wildfires have participants that include rural areas and vegetated areas, and one of their outputs is hydrocarbon flame. The definition of a wildfire is a conflagration that is uncontrolled and combusts material in a vegetated area, whether it be rural or wild.

Conflagration is a type of fire that is defined as a fire which occurs in a large spatial area and poses a risk to human life, animal life, health, and/or property. It is related to the synonyms "blaze" and "large fire."

Flame is a type of gaseous environmental material and is also a type of something that at least has some increased temperature. Additionally, flame is defined as a portion of gas which is emitted by a fire or other exothermic reaction, is of increased temperature, and typically emits light in the visible range.

A hydrocarbon flame is defined as a flame produced by the combustion of hydrocarbon fuel. It is identical to and a type of flame that results from the intersection of a combustion process and the utilization of hydrocarbon-based environmental materials. Specifically, this type of flame is characterized by its output, which is derived from the combustion process that inputs hydrocarbon-based materials. Additionally, a hydrocarbon flame is classified as a type of entity that is primarily composed of substances found at the intersection of dioxygen, carbon dioxide, dinitrogen, and water vapor.

A forest fire is defined as a wildfire that occurs in a forest, primarily consuming vegetation as fuel. It is a type of land fire and also falls under the category of events that occur in at least some forested areas. Additionally, a forest fire is characterized as an event that involves a forest ecosystem as a participant. Furthermore, it is a specific occurrence that requires, as an input, entities that are both part of the Viridiplantae kingdom and partially comprise a forest ecosystem. In essence, a forest fire is equivalent to an event that happens at the intersection of a land fire and events occurring within the union of forested areas, forest biomes, and forest ecosystems.

Mass gaseous flow is a type of mass fluid flow and is also a type of phenomenon that involves at least some gaseous environmental material. It is defined as a process whereby a large volume of gas moves due to a disequilibrium of physical forces. Additionally, mass gaseous flow is synonymously related to wind.

Atmospheric wind is a type of mass gaseous flow and also a type of atmospheric process. It has a broad synonym, "wind", and is related to the synonym "A mass gaseous flow which occurs in a planet's atmosphere due to internal pressure disequilibria."

Stellar wind is a type of mass plasma flow and is also considered as something that includes stellar radiation and involves a star as a participant. It is defined as a stream of plasma primarily composed of electrons, protons, and alpha particles that are ejected from the upper atmosphere of a star. Additionally, stellar wind is related to and has a synonym, Solar wind.

Planetary wind is a type of mass gaseous flow that involves at least one participant composed primarily of materials that are a combination of gaseous environmental substances and are influenced by atmospheric escape. It is also synonymous with a phenomenon where planetary atmospheric gases flow into outer space, known as atmospheric escape.

Mass plasma flow is a type of mass fluid flow and also a type that involves at least some plasma as a participant. It is defined as a process whereby a large volume of plasma moves due to a disequilibrium of physical forces.

Gaseous environmental material is defined as a material entity composed of one or more chemical entities, which neither has an independent shape nor volume but tends to expand indefinitely. It is identical to something that is both an environmental material and possesses at least some quality of a gas. Furthermore, gaseous environmental material is categorized as a type of fluid environmental material, as well as a type of entity that has at least some quality of a gas. Additionally, gaseous environmental material is narrowly synonymous with gas.

Plasma is a type of fluid environmental material that is defined as a material entity composed of a volume of unbound positive and negative particles in roughly equal numbers. It conducts electricity and possesses internal magnetic fields.

An astronomical body, which is a type of astronomical object, is defined as an object that is naturally occurring, bound together by gravitational or electromagnetic forces, and surrounded by space. Furthermore, it is also related to the synonym "celestial body."

A planet is a type of astronomical body. It is defined as an astronomical body orbiting a star or stellar remnant that is massive enough to be rounded by its own gravity, is not massive enough to cause thermonuclear fusion, and has cleared its neighboring region of planetesimals.

A star is an astronomical body, a mass of environmental material, and something that is at least composed primarily of some plasma. It is defined as an astronomical object which is composed primarily of luminous plasma held in a spherical form by gravitational forces.

A planetary moon is a type of astronomical body, defined as an astronomical body that orbits a planet of comparatively greater mass. It is broadly synonymous with "moon" and is also related to the term "natural satellite."
