A tectonic lake is a type of lake and also falls into the category of entities that intersect with those that are at least contained within some depressed landform and those that are at least formed as a result of some tectonic movement. Moreover, a tectonic lake is defined as a lake which is contained in a depression formed by the deformation and resulting lateral and vertical movements of the Earth's lithosphere.

Tectonic movement is a type of material transport process and is also a type of process that involves at least some tectonic plates as participants. It is defined as a process during which pieces of a planetary crust and uppermost mantle move.

Convergent tectonic movement is a type of tectonic movement that occurs in some convergent plate boundary and is characterized by parts of a planetary crust and uppermost mantle moving towards one another. This process is defined as a process during which pieces of a planetary crust and uppermost mantle move towards one another.

Divergent tectonic movement is a type of tectonic movement and is specifically associated with divergent plate boundaries, where it occurs. It is defined as a process during which pieces of a planetary crust and uppermost mantle move away from one another. Additionally, divergent tectonic movement is also known by its exact synonyms: constructive tectonic movement and extensional tectonic movement.

Transform tectonic movement is a type of tectonic movement that typically occurs in some transform plate boundary, indicating it is part of events happening in these locations. It is defined as a process during which pieces of a planetary crust and uppermost mantle move alongside each other in a predominantly horizontal manner, which can be either in a sinistral (left lateral) or dextral (right lateral) direction. Additionally, transform tectonic movement is exactly synonymous with conservative tectonic movement.

A tectonic plate is a type of solid astronomical body part that is at least partially part of the lithosphere, has qualities that are platelike, and overlaps with tectonic plate boundaries. Additionally, it is defined as a part of the lithosphere which is separated from other such parts by geographic faults or similar geomorphological discontinuities.

A tectonic plate boundary is defined as a geomorphological feature formed where two or more tectonic plates move towards, away from, or along one another, resulting in the deformation of the lithosphere. It is recognized as a type of environmental zone characterized by several specific qualities. Firstly, it possesses at least some linearity, indicating its extended nature. Additionally, a tectonic plate boundary overlaps with at least one tectonic plate, underscoring its integral relationship with these plates. Moreover, it is formed as a result of tectonic movement, highlighting its dynamic origin. Furthermore, it consists of at least two tectonic plate components, emphasizing the collaborative aspect of its formation.

A divergent plate boundary is a type of tectonic plate boundary characterized by the process of divergent tectonic movement. It is defined as a geomorphological feature formed where two or more tectonic plates are actively moving away from one another, resulting in deformation of the lithosphere that forms rifts or ridges. This type of boundary is also known by several exact synonyms, including constructive boundary, constructive plate boundary, divergent boundary, extensional boundary, and extensional plate boundary.

A convergent plate boundary is a type of tectonic plate boundary and is also known as a convergent boundary, destructive boundary, or destructive plate boundary. It encompasses processes that include tectonic plate subduction. This geomorphological feature is defined as being formed where two or more tectonic plates actively move towards one another. This movement results in the deformation of the lithosphere, forcing one plate below the other where it subsequently melts in the mantle.

A transform plate boundary is a type of tectonic plate boundary that involves a process incorporating transform tectonic movement. It is defined as a geomorphological feature formed where two or more tectonic plates actively move along one another in either a sinistral (left lateral) or dextral (right lateral) horizontal direction. Additionally, "transform boundary" is an exact synonym for a transform plate boundary, and it is also relatedly referred to as a "transform fault."

Tectonic plate subduction is a type of convergent tectonic movement and has an exact synonym, subduction. It is defined as a convergent tectonic movement process during which one plate moves under another and is forced or sinks due to gravity into a mantle. Furthermore, tectonic plate subduction is a part of some planetary mantle and involves at least one participant that is part of some planetary mantle.

Detritus is a type of organic material and is also classified as something that possesses at least some granular quality. It is defined as an organic material primarily composed of dead particulate matter.

A rift zone is a type of compound astronomical body part, specifically something that at least contains some divergent tectonic movement. It is defined as a compound astronomical body part where extensional tectonic processes occur, and where the lithosphere is being pulled apart. Additionally, "rift" is an exact synonym for a rift zone.

An aeolian lake is a specific type of lake and is categorized under phenomena that are formed as a result of aeolian transport processes. It is defined as a lake which occupies a basin that has been dammed by wind-blown sand. This formation can occur between sand dunes that are oriented by winds or can be a result of wind action under previously arid paleoenvironments.

A landslide lake is a type of lake that is adjacent to or formed as a result of landslide processes. Specifically, it fills a depression where drainage is blocked by solid material transported by a landslide.

Rockslide Lake is a type of landslide lake, which is also a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some rockfall and is formed as a result of some rockslide process. Moreover, Rockslide Lake is defined as a lake which fills a depression where drainage is blocked by solid material transported by a rockslide.

The rockslide process is a type of landslide process and also a type of process that involves participants which are an intersection of solid environmental material and entities primarily composed of rock. A rockslide is defined as a process whereby a large mass of rock moves down a hill or a mountainside. Additionally, the rockslide process has an exact synonym: rockslip.

Karman vortex street is a type of fluid astronomical body part and a type of something that is a union of something aeroform and something at least composed primarily of some hydroform. It is defined as a succession of swirling vortices caused by the unsteady separation of flow of a fluid around one or more blunt bodies. Karman vortex street has exact synonyms: Kármán vortex street and von Kármán vortex street.

An ecosystem is defined as an environmental system that includes both living and non-living components. It is identified as the intersection of an environmental system and the union of entities that, at the very least, include parts of cellular organisms, collections of organisms, and are determined by cellular organisms, collections of organisms, plant anatomical entities, and anatomical entities. Essentially, an ecosystem is a specific type of environmental system characterized by its comprehensive inclusion of both biotic (living) and abiotic (non-living) elements.

A fossil worm burrow is a type of channel and also a type of structure that formed as a result of the fossilization of organic material. It is defined as a channel which was formed as a result of an annelid burrowing through soil, where organic residues lining the burrow have subsequently initiated fossilization.

Fossilization of organic material is a type of environmental system process, which is something that requires at least some organic material as input and produces some mineral material as output. It is defined as a process during which organic substances are replaced with mineral substances while maintaining part of their anatomical organization. Additionally, fossilization of organic material has a broad synonym, which is "fossilization."

Forage material is a type of agricultural environmental material and is also a type of substance that is at least composed primarily of some plant matter. It is defined as material which is primarily composed of the vegetation present in tended pastures, mainly grasses, with an interspersion of legumes and other forbs. Furthermore, forage material has a broad synonym, which is forage.

Feed storage space is a type of agricultural ecosystem defined as a physical space, which may or may not be in a construction, used to store animal feed for agricultural purposes. It is also related to the synonym "feed storage."

Manure storage space is a type of agricultural ecosystem and is defined as a physical space, which may or may not be in a construction, used to store animal manure for agricultural purposes. It is also related to the synonym "manure storage."

Bovine dairy liquid manure is a type of animal manure defined as manure that has been collected directly or indirectly from dairy cattle, including the flushing of manure from concrete feed lanes, free stalls, and milking facilities.
Poultry manure is a type of animal manure, defined as manure which is composed primarily of the feces of poultry.
Heat treated animal manure, which is a type of animal manure, is defined as manure that has been subjected to heat treatment for solidification and/or sterilization purposes.

Composted animal manure is a type of animal manure defined as manure that has undergone a natural process of 'rotting' or decomposition of its organic matter content by microorganisms under controlled conditions.

An animal manure product is a type of manufactured product and also a type of product that is at least composed primarily of animal manure. It is defined as a product which is composed primarily of animal manure that has been heat treated and packaged for commercial or consumer use.

Plant matter is a type of organic material, solid environmental material, and something that is at least composed primarily of some plant anatomical entity. It is defined as organic material which is primarily composed of plant structures, whether living or dead.

A gas planet is defined as a planet which is primarily composed of hydrogen and helium. It is categorized as a type of planet and also as a type of mass of environmental material. Furthermore, a gas planet is described as something that is at least composed primarily of an astrogeological gas and something that is at least composed primarily of substances that are either hydrogen molecular entities, helium molecular entities, or have the quality of a gas. This definition aligns with the characterization of a gas planet as being equivalent to something that intersects with the criteria of being a planet and being composed primarily of substances that are either hydrogen or helium molecular entities or have gas-like qualities.

A dwarf gas planet is a type of gas planet that is defined as being considerably smaller than a gas giant and possesses a rocky core surrounded by a thick envelope primarily composed of hydrogen, helium, and smaller proportions of volatiles.

A giant gas planet is a type of gas planet that is defined as a gas planet with mass and size comparable to Jupiter and Saturn. Additionally, the term "gas giant" is an exact synonym for a giant gas planet.

Ice is a type of environmental material and is characterized by being something that possesses at least some qualities of being both solid and frozen. Furthermore, ice is defined as an environmental material which either exists in a frozen state or is maintained in a solid state through gravitational forces or pressure.

Astrogeological ice is a type of volatile astrogeological material, which is defined as an astrogeological volatile primarily composed of chemical compounds with freezing points above an approximate threshold of 100 Kelvin. Additionally, astrogeological ice is related to and commonly referred to as ice.

An ice giant is the same as something that is both a planet and at least primarily composed of astrogeological ice. It is a type of planet, a mass of environmental material, and something that is at least primarily composed of astrogeological ice. Moreover, an ice giant is defined as a giant planet which is primarily composed of elements heavier than hydrogen and helium, volatile chemical compounds with freezing points above about 100 Kelvin.

Mini Neptune is a type of gas planet characterized by an atmosphere composed of hydrogen and helium, likely featuring deep layers of ice, rock, or liquid oceans made of water, ammonia, a mixture of both, or heavier volatiles, and a small core made of low-density volatiles. Furthermore, Mini Neptune is synonymously related to the term transitional planet.
A Super Jupiter is a type of astronomical body, defined as an astronomical object which is more massive than the planet Jupiter.

Gravitational motion is a type of environmental system process, defined as a process during which one or more entities move along geodesics in a region of spacetime that has been sufficiently curved towards an entity with sufficient mass and/or energy.

A Hot Jupiter is a type of giant gas planet known for its jovian-scale mass (0.36–11.8 Jupiter masses), short orbital period (1.3–111 Earth days), and proximity to the star it orbits, which gives rise to extreme and exotic atmospheric properties. It also goes by several exact synonyms including epistellar jovian, pegasean planet, pegasid, and roaster planet.

A Hot Neptune is a type of gas planet defined as a gas planet with a mass similar to that of Neptune or Uranus, and it closely orbits its star, usually at a distance of less than 1 Astronomical Unit. Additionally, Hot Neptune has an exact synonym, Hoptune.
A Mega Earth is a type of terrestrial planet, defined as a terrestrial exoplanet which is at least ten times the mass of Earth.

A Super Earth is a type of terrestrial planet with a definition as a terrestrial planet which has a mass higher than Earth's but substantially below the masses of Uranus and Neptune, which are 15 and 17 Earth masses, respectively.

A desert planet is defined as a terrestrial planet whose surface is predominantly occupied by hot deserts. This classification is synonymous with the term "dry planet." Specifically, a desert planet is characterized as a type of terrestrial planet that has, as part of its composition, a planetary surface primarily composed of deserts that exhibit increased temperatures. This highlights the desert planet as both a specific instance of a terrestrial planet and as a body having a significant portion of its surface meeting the criteria of being both desert-like and thermally elevated.

An ocean planet is the same as an entity that intersects a planet and an entity that at least has a part of an entity that intersects a planetary surface and an entity that is at least composed primarily of liquid water. It is a type of planet and also a type of entity that at least has a part of an entity that intersects a planetary surface and an entity that is at least composed primarily of liquid water. An ocean planet is defined as a planet which has a surface layer nearly completely or completely covered by water, and which has a substantial portion of its mass composed of water. Additionally, an ocean planet has exact synonyms including aquaplanet, panthalassic planet, and water world.

An ice planet, which is also exactly synonymous with a cryoplanet, is defined as a planet whose surface layer is nearly completely or completely covered by ice and has a substantial portion of its mass composed of ice. It belongs to the category of planets and is specifically a type of planet that has at least a part that is an intersection of planetary surface and a composition that is primarily made of ice. This definition aligns with the concept of an ice planet being the same as an entity that intersects the characteristics of being a planet and having at least a part that combines the features of a planetary surface and a composition predominantly of ice.

Carbon dioxide ice, which is the same as an intersection of ice and a substance that is at least composed primarily of carbon dioxide, is a type of ice and also a type of substance that is at least composed primarily of carbon dioxide. It is defined as ice that is primarily composed of carbon dioxide and has a related synonym, dry ice.
Methane ice is a type of ice, hydrocarbon-based environmental material, and something that is at least composed primarily of methane. It is defined as ice which is primarily composed of methane.

Ammonia ice is a type of ice that shares the same characteristics as something that is an intersection of ice and something that is at least composed primarily of ammonia. This means ammonia ice is essentially ice primarily composed of ammonia. Additionally, it is defined as ice which is primarily composed of ammonia.

Carbon monoxide ice is a type of ice that is also defined as ice which is primarily composed of carbon monoxide. This means it is the same as something that intersects with ice and something that is at least composed primarily of carbon monoxide. Essentially, carbon monoxide ice refers to ice that is chiefly made up of carbon monoxide.

An iron planet, synonymously known as a cannonball planet, is defined as a planet primarily composed of an iron-rich core with little to no mantle. It is categorized as a type of terrestrial planet that also falls into a niche category, characterized by having part of its structure as an intersection of a planetary mantle and another part that possesses qualities associated with either decreased size or decreased mass. Additionally, an iron planet is recognized for having part of its composition as an intersection of a planetary core, which is chiefly made up of either iron atoms or iron molecular entities. This classification underscores the unique composition and structure of iron planets within the broader category of terrestrial planets.

A lava planet is equivalent to an entity that is a planet and also has a part that is both a planetary surface and composed primarily of lava. This denotes a lava planet as a specific type of planet characterized by having parts that are significant intersections of a planetary surface and entities primarily composed of lava. Moreover, a lava planet is defined as a planet whose surface layer is nearly or completely covered by lava, and a substantial portion of its mass is composed of lava.

A sub-Earth is categorized as a type of terrestrial planet. It is defined as a terrestrial planet with a mass smaller than Earth's. This smaller mass results in two key characteristics: firstly, it lacks a magnetic field that is strong enough to protect its atmosphere from being eroded by stellar wind, and secondly, it experiences comparatively short periods of geological activity unless it is subjected to gravitational tidal forces from a significantly more massive object.
